\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q1)
\series default
: Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact and nonempty, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

 exist and are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact and nonempty, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed, bounded and has at least one element according to the Heine-Borel
 Thm.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is bounded, according to the axiom of completeness, it has a supremem and
 an infimum.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sup\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

, then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s-\epsilon<x$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in K$
\end_inset

.
 And in a similar way it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\left(K\right)\in K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q2)
\series default
: Decide which of the following sets are compact.
 For those that are not compact, show how Definition 3.3.1 breaks down.
 In other words, give an example of a sequence contained in the given set
 that does not possess a subsequence converging to a limit in the set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\N$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The set of natural numbers is not compact.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=2n\in\N$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a divergent, unbounded sequence and thus does not contain any subsequence
 that converges.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\Q\cap\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The set is compact.
 The rational number is not a closed set since every irrational number in
 the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q\cap\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q\cap\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 does not contain all of its limit points and cannot be closed.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cantor set
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cantor set is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and is thus bounded.
 According to the Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem, every bounded sequence contains
 a convergent subsequence.
 The construction of the Cantor set consists of the intersection of an infinite
 number of closed intervals, thus the Cantor set is also closed.
 Since the set is closed, all convergent sequences converge to a limit point
 contained in the set.
 Thus the Cantor set is compact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 1+1/2^{2}+1/3^{3}+\cdots+1/n^{2}\,:\,\N\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Not compact.
 This set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set of partial sums 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\frac{1}{k^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(s_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 converges, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 However, this set contains no limit point.
 To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m+1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{n}-s_{m}=\frac{1}{n^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Due to the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\epsilon<\frac{1}{n^{2}}$
\end_inset

 such that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}\left(s_{m}\right)\cap A$
\end_inset

 only contains 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not contain any limit point.
 Therefore, any convergent subsequence converges to a point not in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not compact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 1,\frac{1}{2},\frac{2}{3},\frac{3}{4},\frac{4}{5},\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Compact.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 The only limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, every sequence has a convergent subsequence which will converge to
 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q3)
\series default
: Prove the converse of Theorem 3.3.4 by showing that if a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\R$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded, then it is compact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a closed and bounded set.
 Then all of it's limit points are contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 According to the theorem about limit points, all sequences contained in
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that have a limit, converge to a limit point in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Lastly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bounded, according to the Bolzano-Weierstrass, every sequence contains
 a subsequence that converges, and these subsequences will converge to a
 limit point in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q4)
\series default
: Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Decide if the following sets are definitely compact, definitely closed,
 both or neither.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $K\cap F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Definitely compact and closed.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is closed, the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $K\cap F$
\end_inset

 is closed and its bounded since 
\begin_inset Formula $K\cap F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{F^{c}\cup K^{c}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Definitely closed.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is bounded, 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{c}$
\end_inset

 is not bounded.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{c}\cup K^{c}$
\end_inset

 is not bounded.
 The closure of any set is closed, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{F^{c}\cup K^{c}}$
\end_inset

 is closed and not bounded.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $K\backslash F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
This is neither definitely compact or closed.
 For example, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\left\{ 0.5\right\} $
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K\backslash F=\left[0,0.5\right)\cup\left(0.5,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K\cap F^{c}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Definitely compact and closed.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K\cap F^{c}\subseteq K$
\end_inset

, it must be bounded.
 And the closure of a set is always closed.
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K\cap F^{c}}$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q5)
\series default
: Decide whether the following propositions are true or false.
 If the claim is valid, supply a short proof, and if the claim is false,
 provide a counterexample.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The arbitrary intersection of compact sets is compact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
True, A compact set is closed an bounded.
 The arbitrary intersection of closed sets is closed.
 Since all of the sets are bounded, the intersection of all of the sets
 must be bounded.
 Thus, arbitrary intersection of compact sets is compact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The arbitrary union of compact sets is compact.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
False.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}=\left[0,n\right]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{k=1}^{\infty}I_{k}=\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 which is not bounded and thus not compact.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be compact.
 Then, the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap K$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
False, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a closed interval and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an open interval contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap K=A$
\end_inset

 which is open.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}\supseteq F_{2}\supseteq F_{3}\supseteq\cdots$
\end_inset

 is a nested sequence of nonempty closed sets, then the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap_{n=1}^{\infty}F_{n}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
False.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}=\left[n,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap_{n=1}^{\infty}F_{n}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q8)
\series default
: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be nonempty compact sets, and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d=\inf\left\{ \abs{x-y}\,:\,x\in K\text{ and }y\in L\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

This turns out to be a reasonable definition for the distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are disjoint, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $d>0$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\abs{x_{0}-y_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We suppose, by contradiction, that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are disjoint, nonempty compact sets and that 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

.
 This means that given an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{x-y}<\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}=\frac{1}{n}$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding elements be 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\in L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{x_{n}-y_{n}}<\epsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can construct the sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are bounded, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 must have subsequences that converge to a point; in fact, they must converge
 to the same point since as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{x_{n}-y_{n}}\to0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 must contain a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, but this is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are disjoint.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that it's possible to have 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

 if we assume only that the disjoint sets 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the set of all natural numbers and 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\left\{ n+\frac{1}{n}\,:\,n\in\N\right\} $
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\inf\left\{ \frac{1}{n}\,:\,n\in\N\right\} =0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
